WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.996 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.996 --> 00:00:03.992 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.992 --> 00:00:13.208 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:13.208 --> 00:00:15.250 align:middle line:84%
CASEY RODRIGUEZ: So let's
continue our discussion

00:00:15.250 --> 00:00:16.870 align:middle line:90%
of sequences of functions.

00:00:16.870 --> 00:00:29.060 align:middle line:90%


00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:31.810 align:middle line:84%
So we had two different
notions of convergence

00:00:31.810 --> 00:00:34.430 align:middle line:90%
of sequences of functions.

00:00:34.430 --> 00:00:37.750 align:middle line:84%
So the first notion was
pointwise convergence.

00:00:37.750 --> 00:00:41.590 align:middle line:90%


00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:43.180 align:middle line:84%
So we have a sequence
of functions,

00:00:43.180 --> 00:00:49.330 align:middle line:84%
f n from some set S to R,
another function, fixed

00:00:49.330 --> 00:00:55.260 align:middle line:84%
function f from S
to R. And then we

00:00:55.260 --> 00:01:07.920 align:middle line:84%
say f n converges to f
pointwise if for every x in S,

00:01:07.920 --> 00:01:11.070 align:middle line:84%
the sequence of real
numbers converges to f of x.

00:01:11.070 --> 00:01:19.050 align:middle line:84%
So if for all x and
S, the limit as n

00:01:19.050 --> 00:01:24.450 align:middle line:84%
goes to infinity of f
n of x equals f of x.

00:01:24.450 --> 00:01:28.740 align:middle line:84%
So I take an x out of
S, stick it into f n.

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:30.630 align:middle line:84%
So now I get a sequence
of real numbers.

00:01:30.630 --> 00:01:35.400 align:middle line:84%
And I should get f of x
as n goes to infinity.

00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:38.640 align:middle line:84%
And then we introduced
the stronger notion

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:45.150 align:middle line:84%
of convergence of functions,
which was the following--

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:53.760 align:middle line:84%
so we have a sequence going from
S to R, function from S to R,

00:01:53.760 --> 00:02:08.979 align:middle line:84%
then we said f n converges to
f uniformly on S if somehow,

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:13.450 align:middle line:84%
across the entire set,
f n gets close to f.

00:02:13.450 --> 00:02:19.150 align:middle line:84%
So here, this statement says if
for each fixed x, eventually,

00:02:19.150 --> 00:02:22.720 align:middle line:84%
f n of x-- so f n
evaluated at that point--

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:25.900 align:middle line:84%
is close to f of x, f
evaluated at that point.

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:30.130 align:middle line:84%
But uniform convergence
says f n is close to f

00:02:30.130 --> 00:02:31.660 align:middle line:90%
across the entire set.

00:02:31.660 --> 00:02:37.690 align:middle line:84%
So if for all epsilon positive,
there exists natural number

00:02:37.690 --> 00:02:48.200 align:middle line:84%
M so that for all n bigger than
or equal to M, for all x in S,

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:55.980 align:middle line:84%
f n of x minus f of x
is less than epsilon.

00:02:55.980 --> 00:03:01.430 align:middle line:84%
Now, if you write out what this
means in terms of epsilon M--

00:03:01.430 --> 00:03:04.230 align:middle line:84%
remember, this is a limit, so
this is a limit of sequences,

00:03:04.230 --> 00:03:08.150 align:middle line:84%
so this means something in
terms of epsilons and M's--

00:03:08.150 --> 00:03:11.570 align:middle line:84%
this would say for all x in
S, for all epsilon positive,

00:03:11.570 --> 00:03:15.010 align:middle line:90%
there exists an M, so on.

00:03:15.010 --> 00:03:19.750 align:middle line:84%
So the x appears at the
front of this definition,

00:03:19.750 --> 00:03:21.700 align:middle line:84%
while here for
uniform convergence,

00:03:21.700 --> 00:03:23.590 align:middle line:90%
it appears at the end.

00:03:23.590 --> 00:03:33.830 align:middle line:84%
That is not just a kind
of meaningless difference

00:03:33.830 --> 00:03:37.070 align:middle line:84%
in the way you write
the definition,

00:03:37.070 --> 00:03:43.100 align:middle line:84%
meaning this is a stronger
statement than if the x is

00:03:43.100 --> 00:03:43.950 align:middle line:90%
appearing here.

00:03:43.950 --> 00:03:46.050 align:middle line:90%
So what am I going on about?

00:03:46.050 --> 00:03:49.130 align:middle line:84%
So first off, we
proved last time

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:55.430 align:middle line:84%
that if I have a
sequence of functions,

00:03:55.430 --> 00:04:05.060 align:middle line:84%
again from some subset S to R,
converging to f uniformly, then

00:04:05.060 --> 00:04:10.430 align:middle line:84%
this implies f n
convergence to f pointwise.

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:15.590 align:middle line:90%


00:04:15.590 --> 00:04:19.630 align:middle line:84%
But now, what I'm
going to prove is

00:04:19.630 --> 00:04:21.399 align:middle line:84%
that in fact,
uniform convergence

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:24.340 align:middle line:84%
is something stronger than
pointwise convergence.

00:04:24.340 --> 00:04:27.550 align:middle line:84%
In other words, this
is a one-way street.

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:31.690 align:middle line:84%
Pointwise convergence does
not imply uniform convergence.

00:04:31.690 --> 00:04:39.590 align:middle line:90%


00:04:39.590 --> 00:04:46.890 align:middle line:84%
And we were just going to look
at a very specific example,

00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:55.260 align:middle line:84%
which I was going to
state as a theorem, which

00:04:55.260 --> 00:04:58.430 align:middle line:90%
is the following--

00:04:58.430 --> 00:05:01.880 align:middle line:90%
let f n of x be x to the n.

00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.955 align:middle line:84%
And now we're looking on
the unit interval, 0, 1.

00:05:04.955 --> 00:05:07.720 align:middle line:90%


00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:22.308 align:middle line:84%
And let f the function that
is 0 if x is in 0, 1, 1

00:05:22.308 --> 00:05:23.680 align:middle line:90%
if x equals 1.

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:30.080 align:middle line:90%


00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:33.920 align:middle line:84%
So first off, let
me from last time--

00:05:33.920 --> 00:05:40.850 align:middle line:84%
or you can even just check by
looking at the form of f n--

00:05:40.850 --> 00:05:45.800 align:middle line:84%
that f n converges
to f pointwise.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.590 align:middle line:90%


00:05:48.590 --> 00:05:55.400 align:middle line:84%
If I take x in this interval
here, so not equal to 1,

00:05:55.400 --> 00:05:58.100 align:middle line:90%
then x is strictly less than 1.

00:05:58.100 --> 00:06:00.050 align:middle line:84%
And if I raise it to a
high enough power over

00:06:00.050 --> 00:06:02.690 align:middle line:84%
and over again, that's
converging to 0.

00:06:02.690 --> 00:06:05.270 align:middle line:90%
So it converges to f of x, 0.

00:06:05.270 --> 00:06:09.950 align:middle line:84%
Now at 1, I just get 1, and
that clearly converges to 1.

00:06:09.950 --> 00:06:12.170 align:middle line:90%
So f n converges to f pointwise.

00:06:12.170 --> 00:06:16.940 align:middle line:90%


00:06:16.940 --> 00:06:27.640 align:middle line:84%
And so the claim is that
for all b between 0 and 1,

00:06:27.640 --> 00:06:29.270 align:middle line:90%
f n converges to f.

00:06:29.270 --> 00:06:30.525 align:middle line:90%
And I guess I could include 0.

00:06:30.525 --> 00:06:32.150 align:middle line:84%
That would just be
looking at one point

00:06:32.150 --> 00:06:38.000 align:middle line:84%
and not very interesting, but
f n converges to f uniformly.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.800 align:middle line:90%


00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:47.120 align:middle line:84%
And the second is f n does
not converge to f uniformly

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:50.995 align:middle line:90%
on the whole interval, however.

00:06:50.995 --> 00:06:54.670 align:middle line:90%


00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:59.830 align:middle line:84%
So maybe it's best to
again draw this picture

00:06:59.830 --> 00:07:01.900 align:middle line:84%
that you're supposed
to think about when it

00:07:01.900 --> 00:07:03.940 align:middle line:90%
comes to uniform convergence.

00:07:03.940 --> 00:07:09.080 align:middle line:84%
So we have the
limiting function, f.

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:20.190 align:middle line:84%
And then we draw a little
epsilon-sized collar

00:07:20.190 --> 00:07:23.610 align:middle line:90%
around the function f.

00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:25.920 align:middle line:90%
And then uniform convergence--

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:28.500 align:middle line:90%
so this is f--

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:33.450 align:middle line:84%
uniform convergence says that
as long as I go far enough out,

00:07:33.450 --> 00:07:39.910 align:middle line:84%
the graph of f n should be
within this little epsilon

00:07:39.910 --> 00:07:44.020 align:middle line:84%
collar, so that f n is
getting close to f uniformly

00:07:44.020 --> 00:07:45.160 align:middle line:90%
across the entire set.

00:07:45.160 --> 00:07:53.840 align:middle line:90%


00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:57.560 align:middle line:84%
So number 2 will
give us a chance

00:07:57.560 --> 00:08:00.980 align:middle line:84%
to negate this definition of
uniform convergence, which like

00:08:00.980 --> 00:08:03.133 align:middle line:90%
I said, you should always--

00:08:03.133 --> 00:08:04.800 align:middle line:84%
so we're actually
doing two things here.

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:08.210 align:middle line:84%
We're giving an example
of uniform convergence,

00:08:08.210 --> 00:08:13.010 align:middle line:84%
and also a sequence of functions
which does not converge

00:08:13.010 --> 00:08:16.740 align:middle line:90%
uniformly to this function.

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:19.710 align:middle line:84%
So we're doing both an
example and non-example,

00:08:19.710 --> 00:08:22.440 align:middle line:84%
which is the best thing to
do for a new definition.

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:27.890 align:middle line:84%
So for the proof of 1, let's
prove uniform convergence.

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:32.054 align:middle line:90%


00:08:32.054 --> 00:08:40.020 align:middle line:90%
So let b be in 0, 1.

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:43.090 align:middle line:90%


00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:48.320 align:middle line:84%
Then the limit as n goes
to infinity of b to the n

00:08:48.320 --> 00:08:51.170 align:middle line:90%
is 0, which implies--

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:53.502 align:middle line:84%
so now I'm getting
ahead of myself.

00:08:53.502 --> 00:08:56.920 align:middle line:90%
Don't write that yet.

00:08:56.920 --> 00:09:00.485 align:middle line:84%
So now we want to prove uniform
convergence of f n to f on--

00:09:00.485 --> 00:09:03.850 align:middle line:90%


00:09:03.850 --> 00:09:08.710 align:middle line:84%
I didn't finish this statement,
f n to f uniformly on b.

00:09:08.710 --> 00:09:11.620 align:middle line:90%


00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:16.270 align:middle line:84%
So I have uniform convergence
on any smaller interval

00:09:16.270 --> 00:09:17.560 align:middle line:90%
other than 0, 1.

00:09:17.560 --> 00:09:21.950 align:middle line:90%


00:09:21.950 --> 00:09:24.155 align:middle line:84%
Sorry about that if that
looked a little weird.

00:09:24.155 --> 00:09:27.290 align:middle line:90%


00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:32.250 align:middle line:84%
So then b n converges to
0 as n goes to infinity.

00:09:32.250 --> 00:09:35.390 align:middle line:84%
And now we want to prove that
f n converges to f uniformly

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:38.190 align:middle line:90%
on this interval 0, b.

00:09:38.190 --> 00:09:40.500 align:middle line:90%
So let epsilon be positive.

00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:44.570 align:middle line:84%
We now have to find an M
so that f n is close to 0

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:48.380 align:middle line:84%
because f is 0 on
such an interval.

00:09:48.380 --> 00:09:52.364 align:middle line:90%


00:09:52.364 --> 00:09:55.880 align:middle line:84%
Now, since b to the
n converges to 0,

00:09:55.880 --> 00:10:02.020 align:middle line:84%
there exists natural
number M such

00:10:02.020 --> 00:10:06.880 align:middle line:84%
that for all n bigger than
or equal to M, b to the n

00:10:06.880 --> 00:10:07.765 align:middle line:90%
is less than epsilon.

00:10:07.765 --> 00:10:10.670 align:middle line:90%


00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:16.270 align:middle line:84%
Then for all n bigger than
or equal to M, we get--

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:17.485 align:middle line:90%
and also for all x--

00:10:17.485 --> 00:10:20.790 align:middle line:90%


00:10:20.790 --> 00:10:29.220 align:middle line:84%
0, b, we get that f
n of x minus f of x--

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:36.700 align:middle line:84%
b is less than 1, so when I
stick it into f, I just get 0.

00:10:36.700 --> 00:10:40.360 align:middle line:84%
This is equal to
x to the n minus 0

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:42.400 align:middle line:84%
in absolute value
is just x to the n

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:47.410 align:middle line:84%
because we're looking
at non-negative x.

00:10:47.410 --> 00:10:50.350 align:middle line:84%
And now x is in
this interval 0, b,

00:10:50.350 --> 00:10:52.210 align:middle line:90%
so it's less than or equal to b.

00:10:52.210 --> 00:10:54.400 align:middle line:84%
So x to the n is
going to be less than

00:10:54.400 --> 00:10:58.150 align:middle line:84%
or equal to b to the n, and
this is less than epsilon.

00:10:58.150 --> 00:11:01.310 align:middle line:90%


00:11:01.310 --> 00:11:09.510 align:middle line:84%
So just as when we looked
at uniform continuity

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:13.500 align:middle line:84%
of a function, it was a
statement like, for all epsilon

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:18.202 align:middle line:84%
there exists a delta which
just depends on, basically,

00:11:18.202 --> 00:11:19.410 align:middle line:90%
the epsilon and the function.

00:11:19.410 --> 00:11:22.200 align:middle line:90%


00:11:22.200 --> 00:11:27.540 align:middle line:84%
Now for uniform convergence,
it looks kind of like pointwise

00:11:27.540 --> 00:11:29.790 align:middle line:84%
convergence, except
now for every epsilon

00:11:29.790 --> 00:11:34.830 align:middle line:84%
you can find an M which does
not depend on the point x.

00:11:34.830 --> 00:11:37.020 align:middle line:84%
So for every epsilon,
you can find an M

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:42.300 align:middle line:84%
depending only on epsilon, and
maybe the function little f.

00:11:42.300 --> 00:11:44.590 align:middle line:90%
But that doesn't depend on x.

00:11:44.590 --> 00:11:49.060 align:middle line:84%
This n here that I
chose, M, depended only

00:11:49.060 --> 00:11:55.550 align:middle line:84%
on b, not the point x, which I
have to stick into this here.

00:11:55.550 --> 00:12:00.930 align:middle line:90%


00:12:00.930 --> 00:12:11.440 align:middle line:90%
So now, let's prove number 2.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:17.380 align:middle line:84%
So first off, let's negate
the definition so that we

00:12:17.380 --> 00:12:18.760 align:middle line:90%
know what we're talking about.

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:31.080 align:middle line:84%
So f n does not converge
to f uniformly on a set S

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:33.960 align:middle line:84%
if there exists a bad--
so every "for all"

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:36.750 align:middle line:90%
becomes a "there exists.

00:12:36.750 --> 00:12:42.240 align:middle line:84%
So if there exists some bad
epsilon 0 positive so that

00:12:42.240 --> 00:12:48.820 align:middle line:84%
for all M, a natural number,
there exists n bigger than

00:12:48.820 --> 00:12:54.620 align:middle line:84%
or equal to M, and
there exists an x in S

00:12:54.620 --> 00:13:04.100 align:middle line:84%
so that f n of x minus f of x is
bigger than or equal to epsilon

00:13:04.100 --> 00:13:04.600 align:middle line:90%
0.

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:10.150 align:middle line:90%


00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:13.480 align:middle line:90%
So this is the negation.

00:13:13.480 --> 00:13:17.590 align:middle line:84%
But why should we not be
surprised that f n does not

00:13:17.590 --> 00:13:21.590 align:middle line:84%
converge to f uniformly on 0,
1, if you believe this picture?

00:13:21.590 --> 00:13:26.275 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at
what's going on here.

00:13:26.275 --> 00:13:29.940 align:middle line:90%


00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:37.445 align:middle line:84%
So let me draw,
now, the graph of f.

00:13:37.445 --> 00:13:41.340 align:middle line:90%


00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:46.470 align:middle line:84%
And let's say I take
epsilon to be 1/4, say.

00:13:46.470 --> 00:14:04.690 align:middle line:90%


00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:08.890 align:middle line:84%
Now this is what my little
epsilon neighborhood of f

00:14:08.890 --> 00:14:18.250 align:middle line:84%
looks like or epsilon tube, or
for epsilon equals 1/4, say.

00:14:18.250 --> 00:14:23.080 align:middle line:84%
It's a tube around
0 up to x equals 1,

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:27.220 align:middle line:84%
and then it's a
little area around 1.

00:14:27.220 --> 00:14:31.150 align:middle line:84%
And now if I were to have
uniform convergence, then as

00:14:31.150 --> 00:14:37.690 align:middle line:84%
long as n is very large, f
n has to be within this area

00:14:37.690 --> 00:14:41.180 align:middle line:90%
that I have here.

00:14:41.180 --> 00:14:43.300 align:middle line:90%
So in fact, let me shade it in.

00:14:43.300 --> 00:14:48.120 align:middle line:90%


00:14:48.120 --> 00:14:52.050 align:middle line:84%
So for f n large, it has
to be within this region

00:14:52.050 --> 00:14:55.310 align:middle line:90%
that I'm coloring in.

00:14:55.310 --> 00:14:59.470 align:middle line:84%
But now, what do we
know about x to the n?

00:14:59.470 --> 00:15:02.560 align:middle line:84%
Well, it starts at
0, and ends at 1,

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:08.190 align:middle line:84%
and looks something like
that, which means here,

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:16.040 align:middle line:84%
always, it leaves this epsilon
tube around f, this epsilon

00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:16.895 align:middle line:90%
collar, I guess.

00:15:16.895 --> 00:15:22.015 align:middle line:90%


00:15:22.015 --> 00:15:24.600 align:middle line:84%
f n leaves the
shaded area, which

00:15:24.600 --> 00:15:28.410 align:middle line:90%
is where it's supposed to stay.

00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:34.420 align:middle line:84%
So I hope this intuitive
explanation is clear,

00:15:34.420 --> 00:15:39.905 align:middle line:84%
and why it shouldn't be too
big of a surprise that f

00:15:39.905 --> 00:15:42.350 align:middle line:84%
n does not converge to
f uniformly on 0, 1.

00:15:42.350 --> 00:15:44.330 align:middle line:84%
We'll see another
reason in a little bit

00:15:44.330 --> 00:15:47.150 align:middle line:84%
why it's impossible
for f n to converge

00:15:47.150 --> 00:15:49.710 align:middle line:84%
to f uniformly when we
talk about the interchange

00:15:49.710 --> 00:15:50.210 align:middle line:90%
of limits.

00:15:50.210 --> 00:15:53.150 align:middle line:84%
But just using
the definition, we

00:15:53.150 --> 00:15:57.500 align:middle line:84%
can prove that f n does not
converge to f uniformly.

00:15:57.500 --> 00:16:03.770 align:middle line:84%
So the negation is that there
exists a bad epsilon 0 so

00:16:03.770 --> 00:16:05.510 align:middle line:90%
that we have all of this.

00:16:05.510 --> 00:16:10.750 align:middle line:84%
So the point is
to choose epsilon

00:16:10.750 --> 00:16:17.040 align:middle line:84%
so that this never
intersects with this epsilon

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:19.800 align:middle line:84%
neighborhood of the
function down here,

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:21.900 align:middle line:84%
never intersects
with this epsilon

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:26.100 align:middle line:84%
neighborhood of just the
point x equals 1, y equals 1.

00:16:26.100 --> 00:16:34.270 align:middle line:84%
So let's choose
epsilon 0 to be 1/4.

00:16:34.270 --> 00:16:42.180 align:middle line:90%


00:16:42.180 --> 00:16:44.850 align:middle line:84%
So now we have to prove for
all n, there exists an n.

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:48.505 align:middle line:90%
So let M be a natural number.

00:16:48.505 --> 00:16:53.050 align:middle line:90%


00:16:53.050 --> 00:17:07.619 align:middle line:84%
Choose n to be M. And choose
x to be, let's say, 1 over 4

00:17:07.619 --> 00:17:14.230 align:middle line:90%
to the 1 over M.

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:15.849 align:middle line:84%
Now, this is a
number less than 1.

00:17:15.849 --> 00:17:20.140 align:middle line:84%
So its n-th root is less
than 1 and also positive.

00:17:20.140 --> 00:17:22.700 align:middle line:90%


00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:34.170 align:middle line:84%
Then this f of x
equals 0, and f sub M

00:17:34.170 --> 00:17:38.280 align:middle line:84%
of this x, which is just
1 over 4 to the 1 over M,

00:17:38.280 --> 00:17:41.850 align:middle line:84%
now raised to the
M-th power, 1 over 4,

00:17:41.850 --> 00:17:51.510 align:middle line:84%
which implies that f sub M of
x minus f of x is equal 1/4,

00:17:51.510 --> 00:17:55.430 align:middle line:90%
which equals epsilon 0.

00:17:55.430 --> 00:17:57.950 align:middle line:84%
Or I guess if you like,
you can write bigger

00:17:57.950 --> 00:17:59.360 align:middle line:90%
than or equal to epsilon 0.

00:17:59.360 --> 00:18:07.860 align:middle line:90%


00:18:07.860 --> 00:18:15.370 align:middle line:84%
So basically, if
you choose any-- so

00:18:15.370 --> 00:18:17.770 align:middle line:84%
there was nothing special
about epsilon 0 being 1/4.

00:18:17.770 --> 00:18:21.640 align:middle line:84%
If you choose anything
less than 1, that would do

00:18:21.640 --> 00:18:22.780 align:middle line:90%
You can check that.

00:18:22.780 --> 00:18:26.080 align:middle line:84%
If I chose 1/2 here, I could
then choose this point x

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:32.050 align:middle line:84%
where f M is far away from
f of x to be 1 over 1/2,

00:18:32.050 --> 00:18:35.440 align:middle line:84%
1/2 to the 1 over
M, just as long

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:38.620 align:middle line:84%
as I don't choose epsilon
0 to be equal to 1.

00:18:38.620 --> 00:18:55.600 align:middle line:90%


00:18:55.600 --> 00:18:59.050 align:middle line:90%
So we have that example.

00:18:59.050 --> 00:19:03.840 align:middle line:84%
And we had another
sequence of functions

00:19:03.840 --> 00:19:08.700 align:middle line:84%
we had looked at last time,
which were these functions that

00:19:08.700 --> 00:19:11.308 align:middle line:90%
look like tents.

00:19:11.308 --> 00:19:13.350 align:middle line:84%
I don't know why I'm making
this axis bigger when

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:14.475 align:middle line:90%
it should be the other one.

00:19:14.475 --> 00:19:20.830 align:middle line:90%


00:19:20.830 --> 00:19:27.530 align:middle line:84%
So there's 1, 1 over n, 1
over 2n, then way up here 2n,

00:19:27.530 --> 00:19:30.135 align:middle line:90%
so at this point.

00:19:30.135 --> 00:19:34.000 align:middle line:90%


00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:35.380 align:middle line:90%
And then it's piecewise linear.

00:19:35.380 --> 00:19:38.730 align:middle line:84%
So then it's just a
straight line down to here.

00:19:38.730 --> 00:19:41.790 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to write
down exactly the equation

00:19:41.790 --> 00:19:51.450 align:middle line:90%
for each piece, and then 0 to 1.

00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:54.480 align:middle line:90%
So this is f n.

00:19:54.480 --> 00:20:01.500 align:middle line:84%
And last time, we proved
that f n converges

00:20:01.500 --> 00:20:05.415 align:middle line:90%
to the function 0 pointwise.

00:20:05.415 --> 00:20:10.480 align:middle line:90%


00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:12.900 align:middle line:84%
But it does not
converge uniformly to 0.

00:20:12.900 --> 00:20:15.550 align:middle line:90%
Again, what's the point?

00:20:15.550 --> 00:20:21.930 align:middle line:84%
The point here is that if I
were to draw a little epsilon

00:20:21.930 --> 00:20:29.630 align:middle line:84%
collar around the function 0, it
would look something like this.

00:20:29.630 --> 00:20:33.460 align:middle line:84%
And f n would have to be
within this little strip

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:35.290 align:middle line:90%
for all n sufficiently large.

00:20:35.290 --> 00:20:38.200 align:middle line:84%
But f n is getting
taller and taller,

00:20:38.200 --> 00:20:42.670 align:middle line:84%
so it always leaves any strip
that I put around the function

00:20:42.670 --> 00:20:44.230 align:middle line:90%
0.

00:20:44.230 --> 00:20:47.110 align:middle line:84%
So f n does not
convert to 0 uniformly.

00:20:47.110 --> 00:20:48.910 align:middle line:84%
We can make a proof
out of that, though.

00:20:48.910 --> 00:20:56.290 align:middle line:84%
So f n does not converge
to 0 uniformly on--

00:20:56.290 --> 00:21:02.000 align:middle line:84%
so I should always tell you
where I'm talking about.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.410 align:middle line:90%
And this should-- on 0, 1.

00:21:05.410 --> 00:21:08.750 align:middle line:90%


00:21:08.750 --> 00:21:09.650 align:middle line:90%
So why not?

00:21:09.650 --> 00:21:11.810 align:middle line:84%
Well, we can take any
epsilon 0, really.

00:21:11.810 --> 00:21:18.530 align:middle line:84%
So let's choose
epsilon 0 to be 1.

00:21:18.530 --> 00:21:21.800 align:middle line:90%


00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:23.347 align:middle line:90%
Let M be a natural number.

00:21:23.347 --> 00:21:29.100 align:middle line:90%


00:21:29.100 --> 00:21:33.450 align:middle line:84%
So we should find an n and
a x so that this inequality

00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:34.660 align:middle line:90%
is satisfied.

00:21:34.660 --> 00:21:39.720 align:middle line:84%
So let's choose n to be
M, x to be 1 over 2M,

00:21:39.720 --> 00:21:40.845 align:middle line:90%
at this point where I peak.

00:21:40.845 --> 00:21:43.970 align:middle line:90%


00:21:43.970 --> 00:21:50.820 align:middle line:90%
Then f of M of x minus f of x--

00:21:50.820 --> 00:21:53.850 align:middle line:90%
f here is just 0.

00:21:53.850 --> 00:21:57.810 align:middle line:84%
The limiting function is 0,
so let me not even put f,

00:21:57.810 --> 00:22:00.370 align:middle line:90%
let me put this 0.

00:22:00.370 --> 00:22:07.665 align:middle line:84%
This equals f M of 1
over 2M, which equals 2M.

00:22:07.665 --> 00:22:09.040 align:middle line:84%
And this is
certainly bigger than

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:12.745 align:middle line:84%
or equal to 1,
which is epsilon 0.

00:22:12.745 --> 00:22:21.770 align:middle line:90%


00:22:21.770 --> 00:22:31.310 align:middle line:84%
Now in a little bit, I'll give
you a whole host of examples--

00:22:31.310 --> 00:22:33.830 align:middle line:84%
it seems like I've only given
you maybe one example up

00:22:33.830 --> 00:22:34.910 align:middle line:90%
to this point--

00:22:34.910 --> 00:22:38.330 align:middle line:84%
of functions which converge
uniformly to something.

00:22:38.330 --> 00:22:44.870 align:middle line:84%
But in a minute, I'll give
you a very useful test

00:22:44.870 --> 00:22:48.800 align:middle line:84%
to decide when a series
involving functions

00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:50.120 align:middle line:90%
converges uniformly.

00:22:50.120 --> 00:22:56.880 align:middle line:90%


00:22:56.880 --> 00:23:01.860 align:middle line:84%
But before we get to that, let's
revisit these three questions

00:23:01.860 --> 00:23:04.800 align:middle line:84%
that we asked in
the last lecture

00:23:04.800 --> 00:23:07.440 align:middle line:84%
in the context of
power series, but now

00:23:07.440 --> 00:23:11.790 align:middle line:84%
in this more general setting
of convergence of functions.

00:23:11.790 --> 00:23:17.475 align:middle line:84%
So now what I'm talking
about-- and this is really--

00:23:17.475 --> 00:23:23.960 align:middle line:90%


00:23:23.960 --> 00:23:29.610 align:middle line:84%
although what I'm about to
say may sound a bit alarming,

00:23:29.610 --> 00:23:32.490 align:middle line:84%
that we're now in essentially
the last week of the class

00:23:32.490 --> 00:23:40.760 align:middle line:84%
and we're really getting to the
first real part of analysis.

00:23:40.760 --> 00:23:46.290 align:middle line:84%
So I was talking with a
professor from Duke one time,

00:23:46.290 --> 00:23:50.997 align:middle line:84%
and he made this funny
observation that somehow

00:23:50.997 --> 00:23:52.830 align:middle line:84%
in math-- and I think
this is not just math,

00:23:52.830 --> 00:23:58.390 align:middle line:84%
but this is a lot of
science-based classes--

00:23:58.390 --> 00:24:02.530 align:middle line:84%
are taught, if you
were to translate it

00:24:02.530 --> 00:24:06.790 align:middle line:84%
into studying a book, it's
like you spend a year studying

00:24:06.790 --> 00:24:11.110 align:middle line:84%
introductions to a
book, and then you

00:24:11.110 --> 00:24:13.630 align:middle line:84%
spend a year studying
middle parts of books,

00:24:13.630 --> 00:24:16.810 align:middle line:84%
and then you spend
another year studying

00:24:16.810 --> 00:24:18.550 align:middle line:90%
the last parts of books.

00:24:18.550 --> 00:24:21.550 align:middle line:84%
So now here, we're
starting to get

00:24:21.550 --> 00:24:25.547 align:middle line:84%
into the middle part of the book
of analysis, not the textbook.

00:24:25.547 --> 00:24:27.130 align:middle line:84%
We're at the end of
that, but at least

00:24:27.130 --> 00:24:29.162 align:middle line:84%
in the grand scheme
of things, which

00:24:29.162 --> 00:24:30.370 align:middle line:90%
is the interchange of limits.

00:24:30.370 --> 00:24:38.650 align:middle line:84%
You have two limiting processes
that you want to interchange.

00:24:38.650 --> 00:24:44.650 align:middle line:84%
In analysis, first God created
the limit, and then man asked,

00:24:44.650 --> 00:24:46.180 align:middle line:90%
can we interchange limits?

00:24:46.180 --> 00:24:48.870 align:middle line:90%


00:24:48.870 --> 00:24:50.650 align:middle line:90%
And so what do I mean by that?

00:24:50.650 --> 00:24:56.830 align:middle line:84%
This is not always
a thing you can do.

00:24:56.830 --> 00:25:01.510 align:middle line:84%
And this is at the
very heart of analysis

00:25:01.510 --> 00:25:03.190 align:middle line:84%
is when can we
interchange limits.

00:25:03.190 --> 00:25:05.990 align:middle line:84%
So let me give you
the simplest example.

00:25:05.990 --> 00:25:15.340 align:middle line:84%
Let's say we have
the following limit--

00:25:15.340 --> 00:25:18.070 align:middle line:84%
so I take the limit as k
goes to infinity of the limit

00:25:18.070 --> 00:25:24.550 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to infinity of
n over k, n over k plus 1.

00:25:24.550 --> 00:25:28.270 align:middle line:84%
So that's just a sequence
depending on n and k.

00:25:28.270 --> 00:25:31.900 align:middle line:84%
Now, as n goes to
infinity, what do I get?

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:35.290 align:middle line:90%
This is just equal to--

00:25:35.290 --> 00:25:39.700 align:middle line:84%
I can multiply the bottom
by k to get rid of this one.

00:25:39.700 --> 00:25:41.830 align:middle line:84%
So then I just get
n over n plus k.

00:25:41.830 --> 00:25:44.150 align:middle line:90%
And remember, k is fixed.

00:25:44.150 --> 00:25:46.160 align:middle line:84%
And then I take the limit
as n goes to infinity.

00:25:46.160 --> 00:25:46.990 align:middle line:90%
So I get 1.

00:25:46.990 --> 00:25:50.880 align:middle line:90%


00:25:50.880 --> 00:25:52.470 align:middle line:84%
So I'm taking the
limit as k goes

00:25:52.470 --> 00:25:54.690 align:middle line:90%
to infinity of this expression.

00:25:54.690 --> 00:25:57.850 align:middle line:84%
Now for each k, when I take the
limit as n goes to infinity,

00:25:57.850 --> 00:26:00.000 align:middle line:90%
I get 1.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:01.680 align:middle line:90%
So I get 1 there.

00:26:01.680 --> 00:26:04.920 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happens if I
interchange the limit,

00:26:04.920 --> 00:26:09.810 align:middle line:84%
and now look at the limit as n
goes to infinity of the limit

00:26:09.810 --> 00:26:18.990 align:middle line:84%
as k goes to infinity of
n over k, n over k plus 1?

00:26:18.990 --> 00:26:23.880 align:middle line:84%
Well, now as k goes to
infinity for each n--

00:26:23.880 --> 00:26:25.440 align:middle line:84%
so remember, I'm
taking the limit

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:31.230 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to infinity of this
expression, which is formerly

00:26:31.230 --> 00:26:35.480 align:middle line:84%
this expression with the
limits interchanged--

00:26:35.480 --> 00:26:40.860 align:middle line:84%
this is equal to 0
over 0 plus 1 equals 0.

00:26:40.860 --> 00:26:44.560 align:middle line:84%
And these two do not
equal each other.

00:26:44.560 --> 00:26:47.565 align:middle line:84%
So it's not always the case
that you can interchange limits.

00:26:47.565 --> 00:26:51.430 align:middle line:90%


00:26:51.430 --> 00:26:54.460 align:middle line:90%
That's the simple fact of life.

00:26:54.460 --> 00:27:00.780 align:middle line:84%
And to be able to make
certain statements,

00:27:00.780 --> 00:27:04.800 align:middle line:84%
do certain
computations, you need

00:27:04.800 --> 00:27:06.270 align:middle line:84%
to be able to
interchange limits.

00:27:06.270 --> 00:27:11.160 align:middle line:90%
And what kind of limits?

00:27:11.160 --> 00:27:15.570 align:middle line:84%
Maybe taking an infinite
sum and integrating,

00:27:15.570 --> 00:27:19.320 align:middle line:84%
or like we stated
in the beginning,

00:27:19.320 --> 00:27:22.110 align:middle line:84%
power series are, in a
sense, a certain limit.

00:27:22.110 --> 00:27:24.660 align:middle line:84%
They're a limit of
partial sums of--

00:27:24.660 --> 00:27:27.730 align:middle line:90%
they're a limit of polynomials.

00:27:27.730 --> 00:27:30.430 align:middle line:84%
And then let's say
differentiation--

00:27:30.430 --> 00:27:31.160 align:middle line:90%
that's a limit.

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:36.200 align:middle line:84%
So a natural question,
like we said last time is,

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:39.650 align:middle line:84%
is the derivative of this
infinite sum the infinite sum

00:27:39.650 --> 00:27:40.400 align:middle line:90%
of the derivative?

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:43.640 align:middle line:84%
Those are two limiting
processes which we're

00:27:43.640 --> 00:27:46.520 align:middle line:90%
asking can we interchange.

00:27:46.520 --> 00:27:50.060 align:middle line:84%
So the three questions,
again, that I

00:27:50.060 --> 00:27:52.130 align:middle line:84%
asked in terms of
power series, I'm

00:27:52.130 --> 00:27:58.430 align:middle line:84%
going to now frame again
in this general setting.

00:27:58.430 --> 00:28:14.090 align:middle line:84%
So if f n, S to R, f from S
to R, and f n converges to f--

00:28:14.090 --> 00:28:16.790 align:middle line:84%
maybe pointwise or
uniformly, so let's

00:28:16.790 --> 00:28:21.840 align:middle line:84%
leave this open ended for now
because these are the only two

00:28:21.840 --> 00:28:23.700 align:middle line:90%
notions we have of convergence--

00:28:23.700 --> 00:28:30.620 align:middle line:90%


00:28:30.620 --> 00:28:31.970 align:middle line:90%
and let me make--

00:28:31.970 --> 00:28:39.010 align:middle line:90%


00:28:39.010 --> 00:28:42.310 align:middle line:84%
so suppose f n is from
S to R, f is S to R,

00:28:42.310 --> 00:28:45.980 align:middle line:84%
and f n converges to f
pointwise or uniformly,

00:28:45.980 --> 00:28:48.250 align:middle line:84%
and this sentence is
not written very well,

00:28:48.250 --> 00:29:02.910 align:middle line:84%
and f n is continuous for
all n, then is f continuous?

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:07.020 align:middle line:84%
So suppose we have a sequence of
continuous functions converging

00:29:07.020 --> 00:29:12.120 align:middle line:84%
to another function f, either
pointwise or uniformly.

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:13.632 align:middle line:84%
Is the limiting
function continuous?

00:29:13.632 --> 00:29:15.090 align:middle line:84%
And I'll explain
it in a minute why

00:29:15.090 --> 00:29:17.040 align:middle line:84%
this is a limiting,
kind of asking

00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:19.080 align:middle line:90%
can we interchange two limits.

00:29:19.080 --> 00:29:30.330 align:middle line:84%
Second question is
suppose f n from a, b to R

00:29:30.330 --> 00:29:46.860 align:middle line:84%
is differentiable for
all n, f from a, b to R,

00:29:46.860 --> 00:29:51.600 align:middle line:84%
and we have that f
n converges to f--

00:29:51.600 --> 00:29:53.670 align:middle line:84%
either pointwise
or uniform, we're

00:29:53.670 --> 00:29:56.950 align:middle line:84%
leaving this open
ended for now--

00:29:56.950 --> 00:30:00.460 align:middle line:84%
and the derivatives also
converge, say to some function

00:30:00.460 --> 00:30:14.010 align:middle line:90%
g, then is f differentiable?

00:30:14.010 --> 00:30:19.910 align:middle line:84%
And is the limit
of the derivatives

00:30:19.910 --> 00:30:22.040 align:middle line:84%
equal to the derivative
of the limit?

00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:30.870 align:middle line:90%


00:30:30.870 --> 00:30:36.300 align:middle line:84%
And then the last question-- so
this is the third main limiting

00:30:36.300 --> 00:30:39.150 align:middle line:84%
process we've seen in this
class, which is integration--

00:30:39.150 --> 00:30:44.540 align:middle line:90%


00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:53.110 align:middle line:84%
suppose f n is a sequence
of continuous functions,

00:30:53.110 --> 00:31:03.900 align:middle line:84%
f is a continuous
function, and f n converges

00:31:03.900 --> 00:31:07.350 align:middle line:84%
to f-- again, maybe either
pointwise or uniformly,

00:31:07.350 --> 00:31:09.240 align:middle line:84%
we're leaving this
open ended for now.

00:31:09.240 --> 00:31:12.950 align:middle line:90%


00:31:12.950 --> 00:31:19.730 align:middle line:84%
Does limit of the
integrals equal

00:31:19.730 --> 00:31:21.110 align:middle line:90%
the integral of the limit?

00:31:21.110 --> 00:31:33.190 align:middle line:90%


00:31:33.190 --> 00:31:35.990 align:middle line:90%
Now again, I want you to--

00:31:35.990 --> 00:31:40.090 align:middle line:84%
it's really, I guess,
more clear here,

00:31:40.090 --> 00:31:43.040 align:middle line:84%
the fact that we're asking
about interchanging two limits.

00:31:43.040 --> 00:31:46.180 align:middle line:84%
So here, we have
this integration

00:31:46.180 --> 00:31:49.600 align:middle line:84%
is just a symbol for taking
this limiting process,

00:31:49.600 --> 00:31:52.210 align:middle line:84%
where you take a sequence
of partitions of a, b

00:31:52.210 --> 00:31:55.810 align:middle line:84%
with norm converging to 0, then
the integral from a to b of f

00:31:55.810 --> 00:32:01.120 align:middle line:84%
n-- this is defined to be
this limit of Riemann sums.

00:32:01.120 --> 00:32:03.490 align:middle line:84%
So this is a limiting
process here,

00:32:03.490 --> 00:32:06.950 align:middle line:84%
although I'm writing it
with this simple notation.

00:32:06.950 --> 00:32:09.130 align:middle line:84%
So I'm asking it,
can I take this limit

00:32:09.130 --> 00:32:10.840 align:middle line:90%
as n goes to infinity?

00:32:10.840 --> 00:32:13.510 align:middle line:84%
And can I interchange it
with this limiting process?

00:32:13.510 --> 00:32:19.800 align:middle line:84%
Now, for continuity, it's
maybe a little more hidden

00:32:19.800 --> 00:32:21.540 align:middle line:84%
on what's the
interchange of limits

00:32:21.540 --> 00:32:23.070 align:middle line:90%
that you're really looking at.

00:32:23.070 --> 00:32:26.940 align:middle line:90%
So it looks more like this.

00:32:26.940 --> 00:32:44.164 align:middle line:84%
So remember, for 1, we're
asking suppose x is in set S,

00:32:44.164 --> 00:32:59.510 align:middle line:84%
x n is a sequence converging
to x, then basically,

00:32:59.510 --> 00:33:00.280 align:middle line:90%
can we do this?

00:33:00.280 --> 00:33:05.910 align:middle line:90%


00:33:05.910 --> 00:33:10.800 align:middle line:84%
Now I would like to show that
f of x is equal to the limit

00:33:10.800 --> 00:33:14.070 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to infinity
of f of x sub n.

00:33:14.070 --> 00:33:22.000 align:middle line:84%
So let me actually make this
an m, and use two different--

