so I'm saying that I'm now
choosing this delta that

00:49:45.990 --> 00:49:51.120 align:middle line:84%
came from here, which came from
f sub capital M. Capital M came

00:49:51.120 --> 00:49:55.890 align:middle line:90%
from this, what I needed here.

00:49:55.890 --> 00:49:58.410 align:middle line:90%


00:49:58.410 --> 00:50:02.780 align:middle line:84%
So now, if I look f of x minus
f of c, which I want to show

00:50:02.780 --> 00:50:07.950 align:middle line:84%
is less than epsilon,
now if I add and subtract

00:50:07.950 --> 00:50:12.120 align:middle line:84%
f sub M of x and f sub M
of c and use the triangle

00:50:12.120 --> 00:50:14.910 align:middle line:84%
inequality, this is
less than or equal to f

00:50:14.910 --> 00:50:25.740 align:middle line:84%
of x minus f sub M of x plus f
sub M of x minus f sub M of c

00:50:25.740 --> 00:50:34.540 align:middle line:90%
plus f sub M of c minus f of c.

00:50:34.540 --> 00:50:39.430 align:middle line:84%
So I just added and subtracted
f sub M of x and f of M of c,

00:50:39.430 --> 00:50:43.510 align:middle line:84%
and then used the
triangle inequality.

00:50:43.510 --> 00:50:49.230 align:middle line:84%
Now, by this estimate
here, since I'm

00:50:49.230 --> 00:50:53.250 align:middle line:84%
looking at a particular
n basically equal to M,

00:50:53.250 --> 00:50:56.340 align:middle line:84%
I have this is less
than epsilon over 3

00:50:56.340 --> 00:50:59.770 align:middle line:90%
no matter what y is in this set.

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:02.880 align:middle line:84%
So then certainly for x, I will
have this is less than epsilon

00:51:02.880 --> 00:51:05.420 align:middle line:90%
over 3.

00:51:05.420 --> 00:51:08.240 align:middle line:84%
How I chose delta,
remember, was to guarantee

00:51:08.240 --> 00:51:11.000 align:middle line:84%
that this would be less
than epsilon over 3

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.235 align:middle line:84%
as long as x minus c
is less than delta.

00:51:13.235 --> 00:51:15.602 align:middle line:90%


00:51:15.602 --> 00:51:17.310 align:middle line:84%
And then of course,
this one is less than

00:51:17.310 --> 00:51:21.840 align:middle line:84%
epsilon over 3 again because of
this uniform closeness of f M

00:51:21.840 --> 00:51:22.740 align:middle line:90%
to f.

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:26.360 align:middle line:90%


00:51:26.360 --> 00:51:29.180 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, for
all absolute value

00:51:29.180 --> 00:51:31.250 align:middle line:84%
of x minus c less
than delta, I have

00:51:31.250 --> 00:51:36.690 align:middle line:84%
f of x minus f of c
is less than epsilon.

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:39.200 align:middle line:90%
And that finishes the proof.

00:51:39.200 --> 00:51:42.350 align:middle line:84%
So if we have uniform
convergence, then--

00:51:42.350 --> 00:51:45.410 align:middle line:90%


00:51:45.410 --> 00:51:47.930 align:middle line:84%
a good theorem
should be able to be

00:51:47.930 --> 00:51:54.020 align:middle line:84%
stated in one sentence, or at
least some simple and easy way

00:51:54.020 --> 00:51:55.160 align:middle line:90%
to remember it.

00:51:55.160 --> 00:51:58.550 align:middle line:84%
What this says is the uniform
limit of continuous functions

00:51:58.550 --> 00:51:59.570 align:middle line:90%
is continuous.

00:51:59.570 --> 00:52:04.180 align:middle line:90%


00:52:04.180 --> 00:52:07.420 align:middle line:84%
So the uniform limit
of continuous functions

00:52:07.420 --> 00:52:08.500 align:middle line:90%
is continuous.

00:52:08.500 --> 00:52:11.550 align:middle line:90%


00:52:11.550 --> 00:52:16.560 align:middle line:84%
Next, we'll show, in a
sense, the uniform limit

00:52:16.560 --> 00:52:21.360 align:middle line:84%
of differentiable
functions is continuous.

00:52:21.360 --> 00:52:24.300 align:middle line:90%


00:52:24.300 --> 00:52:32.870 align:middle line:84%
We're going to do the
simplest statement of that,

00:52:32.870 --> 00:52:35.870 align:middle line:84%
although one can make
stronger statements.

00:52:35.870 --> 00:52:38.550 align:middle line:90%


00:52:38.550 --> 00:52:44.340 align:middle line:84%
But in practice, this one
suffices, really, at least

00:52:44.340 --> 00:52:46.155 align:middle line:90%
where it pops up later in life.

00:52:46.155 --> 00:52:50.050 align:middle line:90%


00:52:50.050 --> 00:52:56.355 align:middle line:84%
But before I get to that
one, let's do 3, which is--

00:52:56.355 --> 00:52:59.270 align:middle line:90%


00:52:59.270 --> 00:53:01.520 align:middle line:84%
let's see, what would be the
short way of saying that?

00:53:01.520 --> 00:53:06.620 align:middle line:90%


00:53:06.620 --> 00:53:09.130 align:middle line:84%
The integral of
the uniform limit

00:53:09.130 --> 00:53:12.340 align:middle line:84%
is the limit of the integrals,
something like that.

00:53:12.340 --> 00:53:14.500 align:middle line:84%
That would be the
short and sweet way

00:53:14.500 --> 00:53:18.970 align:middle line:84%
of stating the following
theorem, which is--

00:53:18.970 --> 00:53:20.440 align:middle line:90%
so this is an answer to 3.

00:53:20.440 --> 00:53:24.480 align:middle line:84%
So we skipped over
2 for a minute.

00:53:24.480 --> 00:53:29.800 align:middle line:84%
Suppose f n is a sequence of
continuous functions on a, b,

00:53:29.800 --> 00:53:33.100 align:middle line:84%
because we're going to be
talking about integrals

00:53:33.100 --> 00:53:34.780 align:middle line:84%
and we've only spoken
about integrals

00:53:34.780 --> 00:53:37.620 align:middle line:90%
for continuous functions--

00:53:37.620 --> 00:53:48.000 align:middle line:84%
suppose f n is a continuous
function on a, b, f from a, b

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:58.840 align:middle line:84%
to R, and f n converges
to F uniformly.

00:53:58.840 --> 00:54:05.740 align:middle line:84%
Note that by what we just
proven the previous theorem,

00:54:05.740 --> 00:54:10.390 align:middle line:84%
this automatically
guarantees that f

00:54:10.390 --> 00:54:11.600 align:middle line:90%
is a continuous function.

00:54:11.600 --> 00:54:14.170 align:middle line:84%
So we can ask about
the relationship

00:54:14.170 --> 00:54:16.810 align:middle line:84%
between the integral
of f and the limit

00:54:16.810 --> 00:54:17.920 align:middle line:90%
of the integrals of f n.

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:21.330 align:middle line:90%


00:54:21.330 --> 00:54:26.250 align:middle line:84%
Then the limit as
n goes to infinity,

00:54:26.250 --> 00:54:32.040 align:middle line:84%
integral from a to b of
f n equals the integral

00:54:32.040 --> 00:54:34.120 align:middle line:90%
from a, b to f.

00:54:34.120 --> 00:54:37.080 align:middle line:84%
So the integral of
the uniform limit

00:54:37.080 --> 00:54:39.360 align:middle line:90%
is the limit of the integrals.

00:54:39.360 --> 00:54:49.720 align:middle line:90%


00:54:49.720 --> 00:54:51.580 align:middle line:84%
So this is just a
sequence of numbers,

00:54:51.580 --> 00:54:54.200 align:middle line:84%
and we want to show it
converges to this number here.

00:54:54.200 --> 00:54:56.620 align:middle line:84%
So let's do this the
old-fashioned way.

00:54:56.620 --> 00:55:00.250 align:middle line:90%


00:55:00.250 --> 00:55:01.630 align:middle line:90%
Let epsilon be positive.

00:55:01.630 --> 00:55:04.460 align:middle line:90%


00:55:04.460 --> 00:55:11.210 align:middle line:84%
Since f n converges
to f uniformly,

00:55:11.210 --> 00:55:21.750 align:middle line:84%
there exists a natural
number M such that

00:55:21.750 --> 00:55:25.610 align:middle line:84%
for all n bigger than or
equal to M, for all x in a,

00:55:25.610 --> 00:55:33.200 align:middle line:84%
b, f n of x minus f of
x is less than epsilon.

00:55:33.200 --> 00:55:37.488 align:middle line:90%


00:55:37.488 --> 00:55:39.030 align:middle line:84%
Now, basically what
we're going to do

00:55:39.030 --> 00:55:41.070 align:middle line:90%
is integrate this inequality.

00:55:41.070 --> 00:55:43.860 align:middle line:84%
And remember, unlike
differentiation, integration

00:55:43.860 --> 00:55:45.270 align:middle line:90%
respects inequalities.

00:55:45.270 --> 00:55:48.410 align:middle line:90%


00:55:48.410 --> 00:55:50.500 align:middle line:84%
And for all n bigger
than or equal to M,

00:55:50.500 --> 00:55:57.920 align:middle line:84%
meaning I'm choosing my
M as this guy for proving

00:55:57.920 --> 00:56:04.085 align:middle line:84%
this limit, if I look at
the integral from a, b of f

00:56:04.085 --> 00:56:07.910 align:middle line:84%
n minus the integral
of a, b to f,

00:56:07.910 --> 00:56:11.240 align:middle line:84%
this is, by linearity
of the integral,

00:56:11.240 --> 00:56:14.990 align:middle line:84%
the integral of f n
minus f, absolute value.

00:56:14.990 --> 00:56:18.530 align:middle line:84%
By the triangle inequality for
integrals, which we proved,

00:56:18.530 --> 00:56:21.470 align:middle line:84%
this is less than or equal
to the integral from a,

00:56:21.470 --> 00:56:25.490 align:middle line:90%
b of f n minus f.

00:56:25.490 --> 00:56:29.600 align:middle line:84%
And what do we know for all
n bigger than or equal to M?

00:56:29.600 --> 00:56:35.420 align:middle line:84%
This function here, f n of x
minus f of x in absolute value,

00:56:35.420 --> 00:56:38.240 align:middle line:90%
is bounded by epsilon.

00:56:38.240 --> 00:56:40.040 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, the
integral of this side

00:56:40.040 --> 00:56:42.830 align:middle line:84%
is going to be less than the
integral of the right side.

00:56:42.830 --> 00:56:45.150 align:middle line:90%
So I did this wrong.

00:56:45.150 --> 00:56:48.330 align:middle line:90%
Let's put a b minus a over this.

00:56:48.330 --> 00:56:55.730 align:middle line:84%
So this is less than integral
a, b epsilon over b minus a.

00:56:55.730 --> 00:56:57.750 align:middle line:84%
And so then I just
pick up this number

00:56:57.750 --> 00:57:06.370 align:middle line:84%
times the length of the
interval, which equals epsilon.

00:57:06.370 --> 00:57:08.520 align:middle line:84%
So for all n bigger
than or equal to M,

00:57:08.520 --> 00:57:10.500 align:middle line:84%
the absolute value
of this integral

00:57:10.500 --> 00:57:14.445 align:middle line:84%
of f sub n minus the integral
of f is less than epsilon.

00:57:14.445 --> 00:57:17.510 align:middle line:90%


00:57:17.510 --> 00:57:20.530 align:middle line:84%
So the integral of
the uniform limit

00:57:20.530 --> 00:57:24.020 align:middle line:90%
is the limit of the integrals.

00:57:24.020 --> 00:57:31.300 align:middle line:84%
So now we'll use this to do
the last interchange of limits

00:57:31.300 --> 00:57:35.655 align:middle line:84%
theorem that I had
in mind, so number 2.

00:57:35.655 --> 00:57:38.520 align:middle line:90%


00:57:38.520 --> 00:57:41.670 align:middle line:84%
And again, this is kind of the
simplest statement, and maybe

00:57:41.670 --> 00:57:44.040 align:middle line:84%
easiest to prove,
that one can make.

00:57:44.040 --> 00:57:46.380 align:middle line:84%
One can make stronger
statements and prove them,

00:57:46.380 --> 00:57:49.150 align:middle line:84%
but in most cases,
this suffices.

00:57:49.150 --> 00:58:09.560 align:middle line:84%
So suppose f in a, b to
R. So this is continuously

00:58:09.560 --> 00:58:16.290 align:middle line:84%
differentiable for
all n, f and g--

00:58:16.290 --> 00:58:20.880 align:middle line:84%
these are two functions
from a, b to R--

00:58:20.880 --> 00:58:33.310 align:middle line:84%
and f n converges to f uniformly
on a, b, and the derivatives

00:58:33.310 --> 00:58:35.815 align:middle line:84%
converge uniformly
to this function g.

00:58:35.815 --> 00:58:45.530 align:middle line:90%


00:58:45.530 --> 00:58:49.390 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, I don't
even need this.

00:58:49.390 --> 00:58:50.710 align:middle line:90%
We just say pointwise.

00:58:50.710 --> 00:58:53.760 align:middle line:90%


00:58:53.760 --> 00:58:58.770 align:middle line:84%
So I only need uniform
convergence of the derivatives

00:58:58.770 --> 00:59:02.820 align:middle line:84%
if I'm assuming everything is
continuously differentiable,

00:59:02.820 --> 00:59:04.950 align:middle line:84%
if I'm assuming the
sequences are continuously

00:59:04.950 --> 00:59:06.660 align:middle line:90%
differentiable.

00:59:06.660 --> 00:59:16.320 align:middle line:84%
Then f is
differentiable, in fact,

00:59:16.320 --> 00:59:19.230 align:middle line:84%
continuously
differentiable, meaning

00:59:19.230 --> 00:59:21.030 align:middle line:90%
the derivative is continuous.

00:59:21.030 --> 00:59:26.140 align:middle line:90%


00:59:26.140 --> 00:59:33.670 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative
of f is equal to g,

00:59:33.670 --> 00:59:40.630 align:middle line:84%
meaning that the uniform
limit of the derivatives

00:59:40.630 --> 00:59:44.590 align:middle line:84%
converges to the
derivative of f.

00:59:44.590 --> 00:59:51.120 align:middle line:84%
So again, what this says
is the uniform limit of--

00:59:51.120 --> 00:59:52.628 align:middle line:84%
or at least in
essence and spirit,

00:59:52.628 --> 00:59:55.170 align:middle line:84%
it's not exactly what it says--
but it says the uniform limit

00:59:55.170 --> 01:00:02.060 align:middle line:84%
of continuously differentiable
functions is differentiable,

01:00:02.060 --> 01:00:07.640 align:middle line:84%
and that the derivative of the
uniform limit is the limit of--

01:00:07.640 --> 01:00:10.620 align:middle line:90%


01:00:10.620 --> 01:00:12.270 align:middle line:84%
the derivative of
the uniform limit

01:00:12.270 --> 01:00:14.400 align:middle line:84%
is the uniform limit
of the derivatives.

01:00:14.400 --> 01:00:19.850 align:middle line:90%


01:00:19.850 --> 01:00:22.185 align:middle line:84%
So to prove this, we use
the fundamental theorem

01:00:22.185 --> 01:00:22.685 align:middle line:90%
of calculus.

01:00:22.685 --> 01:00:25.690 align:middle line:90%


01:00:25.690 --> 01:00:32.970 align:middle line:90%
So let x be a point in a, b.

01:00:32.970 --> 01:00:42.390 align:middle line:84%
Then by the fundamental
theorem of calculus,

01:00:42.390 --> 01:00:45.615 align:middle line:84%
if I take f n of
x minus f n of a,

01:00:45.615 --> 01:00:51.265 align:middle line:84%
this is equal to the integral
from a to x of f n prime.

01:00:51.265 --> 01:00:53.640 align:middle line:84%
The integral of the derivative
gives me back the function

01:00:53.640 --> 01:00:55.140 align:middle line:90%
evaluated at the endpoints.

01:00:55.140 --> 01:00:59.780 align:middle line:90%


01:00:59.780 --> 01:01:02.600 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, since I
pointwise convergence,

01:01:02.600 --> 01:01:07.280 align:middle line:84%
these two numbers converge
pointwise to f of x and f

01:01:07.280 --> 01:01:12.450 align:middle line:90%
of a respectively.

01:01:12.450 --> 01:01:15.920 align:middle line:84%
So f of x minus f of
a equals the limit

01:01:15.920 --> 01:01:20.720 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to infinity of
f n of x minus f n of a.

01:01:20.720 --> 01:01:23.648 align:middle line:90%


01:01:23.648 --> 01:01:31.590 align:middle line:84%
And this is equal to, just by
the previous expression, limit

01:01:31.590 --> 01:01:33.870 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to infinity
of the integral from a

01:01:33.870 --> 01:01:38.030 align:middle line:90%
to x of f n prime.

01:01:38.030 --> 01:01:41.340 align:middle line:90%


01:01:41.340 --> 01:01:44.610 align:middle line:84%
Now, these f n primes are
converging to g, this function

01:01:44.610 --> 01:01:46.260 align:middle line:90%
g, uniformly.

01:01:46.260 --> 01:01:48.315 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, the
integrals converge.

01:01:48.315 --> 01:01:49.440 align:middle line:90%
that's what we just proved.

01:01:49.440 --> 01:01:52.170 align:middle line:90%


01:01:52.170 --> 01:01:53.990 align:middle line:84%
So this equals the
integral of the limit.

01:01:53.990 --> 01:01:56.710 align:middle line:90%


01:01:56.710 --> 01:02:01.290 align:middle line:84%
And therefore-- so we started
off with f of x minus f of a,

01:02:01.290 --> 01:02:04.560 align:middle line:84%
and we showed it's equal to
the integral from a to x of g.

01:02:04.560 --> 01:02:14.610 align:middle line:84%
So f of x equals f of a plus
the integral from a to x of g.

01:02:14.610 --> 01:02:17.250 align:middle line:84%
But no, again by the
fundamental theorem of calculus,

01:02:17.250 --> 01:02:26.490 align:middle line:84%
this implies that f
is differentiable.

01:02:26.490 --> 01:02:31.580 align:middle line:84%
And the derivative of f
of x, the derivative of f,

01:02:31.580 --> 01:02:34.070 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the
derivative-- so remember,

01:02:34.070 --> 01:02:37.820 align:middle line:84%
f of a, that's just a
constant-- equals the derivative

01:02:37.820 --> 01:02:39.710 align:middle line:90%
of this function, which is g.

01:02:39.710 --> 01:02:51.580 align:middle line:90%


01:02:51.580 --> 01:02:55.030 align:middle line:84%
I think we have just
enough time to prove

01:02:55.030 --> 01:03:01.770 align:middle line:90%
one more pretty good theorem.

01:03:01.770 --> 01:03:07.050 align:middle line:90%


01:03:07.050 --> 01:03:08.550 align:middle line:90%
Pretty good-- it's very good.

01:03:08.550 --> 01:03:14.000 align:middle line:90%


01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:21.500 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll use it
in our next lecture

01:03:21.500 --> 01:03:25.130 align:middle line:84%
to discuss, or at
least conclude,

01:03:25.130 --> 01:03:27.545 align:middle line:84%
some answers that we originally
asked about power series.

01:03:27.545 --> 01:03:32.090 align:middle line:90%


01:03:32.090 --> 01:03:37.090 align:middle line:84%
So this theorem is due to
the godfather, Weierstrass.

01:03:37.090 --> 01:03:40.372 align:middle line:84%
I don't know, did I refer to
him as godfather or Riemann

01:03:40.372 --> 01:03:41.080 align:middle line:90%
as the godfather?

01:03:41.080 --> 01:03:42.970 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, I think
it was Weierstrass

01:03:42.970 --> 01:03:45.670 align:middle line:84%
that I refer to
as the godfather.

01:03:45.670 --> 01:03:47.110 align:middle line:84%
He proved the
following theorem--

01:03:47.110 --> 01:03:50.320 align:middle line:90%


01:03:50.320 --> 01:03:53.950 align:middle line:84%
when can you guarantee
uniform convergence

01:03:53.950 --> 01:03:55.480 align:middle line:84%
for at least a
series of functions,

01:03:55.480 --> 01:04:00.340 align:middle line:84%
which are limits of partial
sums, so limits of functions?

01:04:00.340 --> 01:04:04.540 align:middle line:84%
And he proved this basically
so he could come up

01:04:04.540 --> 01:04:09.190 align:middle line:84%
with a whole host of examples
of continuous functions

01:04:09.190 --> 01:04:12.825 align:middle line:84%
which are nowhere
differentiable.

01:04:12.825 --> 01:04:14.450 align:middle line:84%
We kind of gave a
proof of this theorem

01:04:14.450 --> 01:04:17.763 align:middle line:84%
when we looked at
that example, when

01:04:17.763 --> 01:04:19.430 align:middle line:84%
we were talking about
differentiability,

01:04:19.430 --> 01:04:24.320 align:middle line:84%
but we didn't state
it as a theorem there.

01:04:24.320 --> 01:04:34.340 align:middle line:84%
So let's take a sequence of
functions f j from S to R,

01:04:34.340 --> 01:04:50.170 align:middle line:84%
and suppose there exists a
sequence M j such that two

01:04:50.170 --> 01:04:51.040 align:middle line:90%
things hold.

01:04:51.040 --> 01:04:53.080 align:middle line:84%
So these are a sequence
of positive numbers.

01:04:53.080 --> 01:05:02.520 align:middle line:90%


01:05:02.520 --> 01:05:04.350 align:middle line:84%
I don't know why I
just erased that, but--

01:05:04.350 --> 01:05:08.070 align:middle line:84%
so we have a sequence
of functions from S to R

01:05:08.070 --> 01:05:12.660 align:middle line:84%
and a sequence of positive
numbers so that these numbers

01:05:12.660 --> 01:05:13.845 align:middle line:90%
dominate the f j's.

01:05:13.845 --> 01:05:24.640 align:middle line:90%


01:05:24.640 --> 01:05:30.540 align:middle line:84%
And 2, they're
summable, so sum from j

01:05:30.540 --> 01:05:41.230 align:middle line:84%
equals 1 to infinity,
